{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529258"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:53:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:53:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14375"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14375"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.01,0.05,0.73,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7070"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114839"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7070"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14375"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96839"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1487"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4653"},{"type":"tags","id":"4654"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43525"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114839"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic for her first antenatal visit. She is 10 weeks pregnant based on her last menstrual period. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. As part of routine antenatal screening, a cervical swab is taken for nucleic acid amplification testing (NAAT). The results come back positive for \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prescribe erythromycin and retest in one week","Defer treatment until the second trimester","Refer to an obstetrician for management","Prescribe azithromycin and arrange partner treatment","Prescribe doxycycline and arrange partner treatment"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprescribe azithromycin and arrange partner treatment\u003C/strong\u003E. Chlamydia is a common sexually transmitted infection. It can lead to serious consequences in pregnancy, including preterm labour, premature rupture of membranes, and postpartum endometritis. It can also be transmitted to the newborn during delivery, potentially causing conjunctivitis or pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this case. While doxycycline is an effective treatment for chlamydia in non-pregnant individuals, it is contraindicated during pregnancy due to the risk of tooth discoloration and inhibition of bone growth in the developing fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeferring treatment until the second trimester\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended. Treating at the time of diagnosis reduces the risk of transmission to the fetus and helps to prevent complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring to an obstetrician for management\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary at this stage. Chlamydia in pregnancy is often effectively managed in the primary care setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing erythromycin and retesting in one week\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate first-line management. While erythromycin is an alternative treatment for chlamydia in pregnancy, azithromycin is preferred due to its better tolerability and simpler dosing regimen. Additionally, retesting should typically be done 3-4 weeks after treatment, not after one week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recommended treatment for chlamydia in pregnancy is azithromycin 1g orally as a single dose. This treatment is safe and effective during all stages of pregnancy. It\u0027s crucial to also treat the sexual partner(s) to prevent reinfection. After treatment, a test of cure should be performed 3-4 weeks later to ensure eradication of the infection. If the test of cure is positive, retreatment and further investigation for potential reinfection or antibiotic resistance may be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chlamydia screening is recommended for all pregnant women at their first antenatal visit.","Azithromycin is the first-line treatment for chlamydia in pregnancy.","Partner treatment and retesting after 3-4 weeks are essential components of chlamydia management in pregnancy."],"references":["Australasian Society for Infectious Diseases (ASID). Management of perinatal infections. Melbourne: The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG); 2014. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96839"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14375"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96839","li